  "text": "We next investigated the role of FFAs in the induction of inflammatory changes in macrophages. Coculture of 3T3-L1 with RAW264 significantly increased the release of FFAs (PϽ0.01; Figure 4A ), which was significantly inhibited by the blockade of TNF-␣ using an anti-TNF-␣ neutralizing antibody (PϽ0.05; Figure 4B ). Saturated FAs, such as palmitate and laurate, significantly induced TNF-␣ mRNA expression in RAW264 (PϽ0.01; Figure 4C ). By contrast, polyunsaturated FAs (PUFAs), such as linolenate and eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA), showed no effects. These observations are consistent with previous reports on FA-induced inflammatory changes in macrophages and myotubes. [CITATION_1] Pretreatment with PD98059 or SP600125 significantly inhibited palmitate-induced upregulation of TNF-␣ in RAW264 (PϽ0.05; Figure 4D ). These observations, taken together, indicate that macrophage-derived TNF-␣ increases the release of FFAs from adipocytes, which, in turn, induces inflammatory changes in macrophages at least partly via the MAP kinase pathways.",
